This walk is an element of the small ring of the 15th, accessible by a staircase via rue Leblanc. The Petite Ceinture, a 32 km railway line, was built around Paris during the Second Empire (1852-1869). The section from Place Balard to Rue Olivier de Serres was closed to travelers in 1934, but remained used by freight trains until the 1980s. Vegetation is gradually taking hold on railway structures, creating habitats conducive to flora and fauna. This railway and natural context that it is up to everyone to preserve favors the creation of this green space which has retained its original wasteland character while integrating into the urban fabric.
Superb little unexpected walk which joins the Georges BRASSENS park in the 15th arrondissement of Paris. A little green paradise in the middle of the hustle and bustle of the city.

Nice walk protected from traffic. Quite a few walkers. Very pleasant because it is quiet. Dogs are accepted, mostly on a leash. Small downsides: 1) overall lacks a little shade, in fact in the middle of summer, it must be more of a way of the cross than a walk. 2) no junction with other small belt paths Damage. But hey, in the middle of Paris, itâ€™s still pretty nice!
A pleasant green stroll, without a car, to discover Paris from another aspect. We come across joggers, dogs, itâ€™s very peaceful and not too long for small children

A disused train line, which is very nice for a break to go for a walk. A nice alternative to the park for dog owners. Unfortunately it's a bit crowded with joggers on the weekend, so I can recommend it during the week. There are different opening times depending on the season. There is now also a cafÃ© :-)

Quiet section during the week, but not too maintained. No bars, toilets, no terraces (for the moment, but there is work in progress so I suppose we will be allowed to do so this summer ðŸ¤ž). No benches, either. Hence the missing star. It would be really wonderful to have benches to sit and enjoy a sandwich or just admire the surroundings instead of getting your clothes dirty trying to find a comfortable corner. Pee smell is also a problem. Brief. This is good, but it could improve.

Pleasant walk without a car. This allows you to see the 'hidden side' of buildings. We have the impression of seeing the 'behind scene' of the neighborhood. Remember to take the path towards Georges Brassens Park (and admire the superb fresco on the building at its entrance). And above all, pay attention to the wooden slats. It would take a little restoration work and perhaps a little more revegetation.
A little unusual stroll on a disused railway line. We enter the privacy of certain building courtyards... some walls are tagged in a very humorous way... it's nice
Very nice to walk in this section of the 15th arrondissement, between the plants and the graffiti of the inner ring road. Walk with family or lovers. A different side of Paris is offered to you!

Everyone knows the High Line in New York. This is the sister in Paris. Located high on an old railway line where trains for CitroÃ«n used to run. You look out over the streets and walk from park to park between greenery and tennis courts. Halfway through a coffee in the old station building.
Very nice place to walk or go for a run. It's a change from the Boulevard or the banks of the Seine. I'll come back....

dogs allowed on a leash. Really nice place
Quiet place, it's cool to walk, run or walk your dog. It's clean enough too.
A great place to think~!!! A natural space that makes you feel like you are not in Paris ^^

Small regional [not to say provincial], I didn't know the place, and it's a nice piece of nature in the middle of the city. There, around 2 p.m. on a weekday, we find sportsmen, dog owners, owners' dogs and a few other urbanites looking for calm. There are developments at the old stations, including a fairly pleasant bar "whose name I haven't noticed". Good research future reader.
